04770nam a22007455i 9781400822607DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t19981999nju    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)984688498  a97814008226077 a10.1515/97814008226072doi  a(DE-B1597)446170  a(OCoLC)979757060  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBQ4570bS48F3813 1998 7aREL0070002bisacsh1 aFaure, Bernard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Red Thread :bBuddhist Approaches to Sexuality /cBernard Faure.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[1998] 4c©1999  a1 online resource (324 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBuddhisms: A Princeton University Press Series ;v100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. The Hermeneutics of Desire -- tChapter 2. Disciplining Sex, Sexualizing Discipline -- tChapter 3. The Ideology of Transgression -- tChapter 4. Clerical Vices and Vicissitudes -- tChapter 5. Buddhist Homosexualities -- tChapter 6. Boys to Men -- tAfterthoughts -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIs there a Buddhist discourse on sex? In this innovative study, Bernard Faure reveals Buddhism's paradoxical attitudes toward sexuality. His remarkably broad range covers the entire geography of this religion, and its long evolution from the time of its founder, Xvkyamuni, to the premodern age. The author's anthropological approach uncovers the inherent discrepancies between the normative teachings of Buddhism and what its followers practice. Framing his discussion on some of the most prominent Western thinkers of sexuality--Georges Bataille and Michel Foucault--Faure draws from different reservoirs of writings, such as the orthodox and heterodox "doctrines" of Buddhism, and its monastic codes. Virtually untapped mythological as well as legal sources are also used. The dialectics inherent in Mahvyvna Buddhism, in particular in the Tantric and Chan/Zen traditions, seemed to allow for greater laxity and even encouraged breaking of taboos. Faure also offers a history of Buddhist monastic life, which has been buffeted by anticlerical attitudes, and by attempts to regulate sexual behavior from both within and beyond the monastery. In two chapters devoted to Buddhist homosexuality, he examines the way in which this sexual behavior was simultaneously condemned and idealized in medieval Japan. This book will appeal especially to those interested in the cultural history of Buddhism and in premodern Japanese culture. But the story of how one of the world's oldest religions has faced one of life's greatest problems makes fascinating reading for all.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBuddhismvSocial aspects. 0aBuddhismxSocial aspects. 0aRELIGIONvBuddhismvGeneral. 0aSexvReligious aspectsvBuddhism. 0aSexxReligious aspectsxBuddhism. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / General (see also PHILOSOPHY / Buddhist).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Archive (pre 2000) eBook Packagez978311064968008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140082260740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400822607423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400822607.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  a978-3-11-064968-0  Asian Studies Archive (pre 2000) eBook Package  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSH